Vice President Mike Pence delivered a speech at the Ronald Reagan Building Amphitheater in Washington, D.C. to commemorate the 15th anniversary of the United States Department of Homeland Security (DHS). Pence expressed gratitude and respect for the men and women of DHS, acknowledging their dedication to safeguarding the American people, homeland, and values. He also praised the creation of DHS in response to the September 11th terrorist attacks and recognized the leadership of previous secretaries such as Tom Ridge and Michael Chertoff. Pence highlighted the various agencies within DHS, such as the Transportation Security Administration (TSA), Customs and Border Protection (CBP), Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), Coast Guard, Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA), and Secret Service. He emphasized the importance of securing the borders and enforcing immigration laws. Pence also touched on the recent acts of violence in the United States and vowed to work with Congress to make schools and communities safer. He concluded by commending the dedication and integrity of the men and women of DHS and expressed confidence in their ability to keep the nation safe.